    <div class="card doc-section" id="overview">
      <div class="card-header"><span class="card-header-icon">&#x1F50D;</span><div><div class="card-title">Overview</div><div class="card-subtitle">What the DoD Banner Library provides</div></div></div>
      <div class="card-body prose">
        <p>The <strong>DoD Banner Library</strong> is a managed Power Platform solution providing reusable, GCC High-safe banner assets for <strong>Power Pages</strong>, <strong>Canvas Apps</strong>, and <strong>Model-Driven Apps</strong>. A single solution import delivers all assets with no external dependencies.</p>
        <p>Two banner types are included:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>DoD Consent Banner</strong> &mdash; a blocking modal overlay requiring user acknowledgment on first visit. Consent tracked via browser cookie. Vanilla JavaScript, zero CDN calls.</li>
          <li><strong>CUI Classification Mark</strong> &mdash; a color-coded top or bottom classification bar on any container element via a <code>data-classification</code> attribute. No JavaScript required.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The solution also includes the <strong>DoD Banner Library Management</strong> model-driven app, providing in-environment access to this documentation, release notes, and the Power Pages web template source directly from the app switcher.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-tip"><span class="callout-icon">&#x2705;</span><div><strong>GCC High / IL4/IL5 safe.</strong> All assets are self-contained &mdash; no external CDN calls, no third-party scripts. The jQuery dependency present in prior versions was removed in v1.0.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card doc-section" id="post-import">
      <div class="card-header"><span class="card-header-icon">&#x2705;</span><div><div class="card-title">Post-Import Checklist</div><div class="card-subtitle">Complete these steps after importing the solution</div></div></div>
      <div class="card-body">
        <div class="steps">
          <div class="step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-content"><div class="step-title">Verify web resources</div><div class="step-desc">Confirm all six web resources are present: <code>dodbl_bannercore</code>, <code>dodbl_dodconsentbanner</code>, <code>dodbl_cuiconsentbanner</code>, <code>dodbl_webtemplatesource</code>, <code>dodbl_docs</code>, and <code>dodbl_release-notes</code>. Also confirm the <strong>DoD Banner Library Management</strong> app (<code>dodbl_DoDBannerLibraryManagement</code>) is visible in the app switcher. If any components are missing, re-import the managed solution.</div></div></div>
          <div class="step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-content"><div class="step-title">Power Pages &mdash; create web files</div><div class="step-desc">For each portal, create two Web File records in the Portal Management app. Copy CSS from <code>dodbl_bannercore</code> and JS from <code>dodbl_dodconsentbanner</code>. Set partial URLs to <code>/banner-core.css</code> and <code>/dod-consent-banner.js</code>, parent page to Home, publishing state to Published. See the <a href="#dod-consent">DoD Consent Banner</a> section for full steps.</div></div></div>
          <div class="step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-content"><div class="step-title">Power Pages &mdash; create the Web Template and add to site header</div><div class="step-desc">Open <code>dodbl_webtemplatesource</code> in a browser, copy the Liquid source, and paste it into a new Web Template named <code>dod-consent-banner</code> in Portal Management. Then add <code>{% include 'dod-consent-banner' %}</code> to your site&rsquo;s header Web Template. Full instructions are inside <code>dodbl_webtemplatesource</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="step"><div class="step-num" style="background:#5e5e5e">4</div><div class="step-content"><div class="step-title">Canvas Apps &mdash; enable code components <span class="badge badge-future">Coming in v1.1</span></div><div class="step-desc">A PCF Virtual Component (<code>DodBannerControl</code>) is planned for v1.1. Toggle <strong>Enable code components</strong> in environment Power Apps settings when available. Requires Power Apps Premium or Managed Environment.</div></div></div>
          <div class="step"><div class="step-num" style="background:#5e5e5e">5</div><div class="step-content"><div class="step-title">Model-Driven Apps &mdash; add form script <span class="badge badge-future">Coming in v1.1</span></div><div class="step-desc">A JavaScript web resource for Model-Driven App form <code>OnLoad</code> is planned for v1.1, providing the consent modal without PCF or a Premium license.</div></div></div>
          <div class="step"><div class="step-num" style="background:#5e5e5e">6</div><div class="step-content"><div class="step-title">Power Pages &mdash; grant consent record table permission <span class="badge badge-future">Coming in v1.1</span></div><div class="step-desc">A Dataverse consent audit table (<code>dodbl_consent_record</code>) is planned for v1.1. After it is added, grant the Authenticated Users web role <strong>Create</strong> access on that table.</div></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
